          "body": "The chapter opens with Herod's terrified speculation about Jesus (14:1-2) and closes with the disciples' worship of Him (14:33). The same question runs through both ends — *who is this?* — but two answers are offered. Herod, ruled by oaths and dinner guests, can produce only the projection of his own guilt: *this is John, raised*. The disciples, walked through wilderness-feeding and water-walking, produce the true confession: *truly You are the Son of God*. The chapter's pastoral theology is here: fear of the wrong things produces tyranny in Herod and sinking in Peter; fear of the right One — translated into worship — produces stability. *Take courage, it is I; do not be afraid* (14:27) is the chapter's central word."
